<p align='center'><strong><font color='#0E024D' face='Arial'>A STUDY OF THE MODULATION ROD, JANUARY 26, 2000.</font></strong></p>
<div align='center'><center>

<table border='0' cellpadding='0' cellspacing='0' width='85%'>
  <tr>
    <td width='100%'>
<p><span style='mso-bidi-font-size: 14.0pt; font-style: normal'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Introduction<o:p>
</o:p>
</b>
</font>
</span></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>I have seen and been a part of the debate on the usefulness of our new
level 44 summon, Modulating Rod.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Debates
have raged in many forums in many threads and yet most of what is posted is
opinion.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Here is my attempt to
quantify the benefits of the Rod.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Take
issue or agree as you see fit.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>This
was as much for my own information as for yours.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>My hope is that in sharing it with you, we will have a basis for further
debate that isn’t tied up in opinion.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><span style='mso-bidi-font-size: 14.0pt; font-style: normal'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>The
Spell<o:p>
 </b>
</o:p>
</font>
</span></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Magicians can now summon a
Modulation Rod, which has a single “charge” of Modulation.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>(Technical note: this item is consumable.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>That means when the effect is used, the item vanishes.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Therefore one could argue it isn’t a charge).<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The effect converts 225 health points to 150 mana points instantly.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The spell is a level 44 summon, meaning only magicians level 44 or higher
can cast this spell.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>The Rod is LORE (can only have 1 at a time) and NORENT (it
will vanish on logout of link death).<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><span style='mso-bidi-font-size: 14.0pt; font-style: normal'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>The
Weapon<o:p>
 </b>
</o:p>
</font>
</span></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Rod is actually a 1HB
weapon with 8/26 stats.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>It’s a
decent weapon.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>However, with the
exception of Monks it isn’t likely to be useful to those levels 44+.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Those who have melee skills either have better weapons (warriors,
rangers, paladins, shadow knights, rogues) or are casting rather than swinging a
weapon (clerics, shaman, druids).<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Pure
casters don’t melee at this level and therefore won’t use this as a weapon.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>All in all, it’s a good weapon.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>However,
its use solely as a weapon is very limited.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><span style='mso-bidi-font-size: 14.0pt; font-style: normal'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>The
Effect<o:p>
 </b>
</o:p>
</font>
</span></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Rod’s real power comes
from its ability to modulate.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>That
is, exchange health for mana.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>The
exchange is very good at 66.6% (2 mana for each 3 health).<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>However, it is limited to one-time use.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>Once used, it vanishes.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The negative drain on health will be stopped by Rune.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>As a Magician has no class-based magical skin, I was only able to test
with Rune.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>(I had an Enchanter friend cast it on me to test).<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Of
course, the Rune is negated by the effect.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Net, net is if you have Rune up when using this effect, you will take no
damage, lose the Rune and gain 150 mana.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><span style='mso-bidi-font-size: 14.0pt; font-style: normal'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>The
Executive Summary<o:p>
</o:p>
</b>
</font>
</span></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Rod can be summarized as
having an effect that will do an approximate 300 points of damage to a mob in
exchange for 225 points of damage to its user.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The potential for the Rod to do more than 300 damage is small, but not to
be ignored.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>In dire emergencies,
the Rod may supply the mana needed to evacuate, but the conditions for this to
happen are rare.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>The Rod is not a
replacement for the manastone—it is not viable for buffing.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>It has limited use in mass resurrections.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>It is an ideal weapon for monks who’d like to play around with 1HB.<o:p>
&nbsp;
</font></p>
<hr size='1'>
<p><span style='mso-bidi-font-size: 14.0pt; font-style: normal'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>The
Detail<o:p>
</o:p>
</b>
</font>
</span></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Hypothetical Party: Cleric,
Enchanter, Magician, Rogue, Warrior, and Wizard<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Now, don’t take issue with
the merits of this party.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>I think
it’s typical and viable.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>In any
event, it’s for example’s sake.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><b><font face='Arial' size='2'><u>Scenario 1- Buffing<o:p>
</u>
</o:p>
</font></b></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Enchanter and Cleric of
this party each have pre-fight buffing duties.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Buffing can take a lot of mana.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Those
lucky enough to possess manastones likely make heavy use of them while buffing.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Manastones convert 60 health points to 20 mana points (33% efficiency).<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>Can the Rod assist the party in this scenario?<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Each summon will require 200
mana from the Magician and 225 health from its user to return 150 mana to its
user.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>In this scenario, the cost to
produce and the cost to consume the Modulation effect make the return negative
to the party.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span><o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><b><font face='Arial' size='2' color='#000000'>Conclusion: </font></b></p>
<p><b><span style='color: red'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Rod isn’t a tool for buffing like the
manastone.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></span></b></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>&nbsp;</font></p>
<p><b><font face='Arial' size='2'><u>Scenario 2-Mass Resurrection<o:p>
</u>
</o:p>
</font></b></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>I’ve seen it argued that the Rod will be of great benefit in the planes for mass resurrections.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>That is, each person has a Rod prior to going to the plane and if killed,
gives their Rod to the Cleric upon resurrect.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>How useful is the Rod in this case?<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>If the Cleric is casting the
level 49 resurrection spell, it costs 700 mana.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>A Cleric likely complete heals those just resurrected, but to
give favor to the Rod, lets assume those resurrected are healed by druids or
shaman rather than the Cleric with resurrection duty.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Cleric resurrects 5 people: 5 x
700 = 3500 mana needed; 6 rods (Cleric’s own and 5 resurrected player’s
rods) provide 800 mana at a cost of 1350 health.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>Basically, for each 6 rods, the Cleric gets a “free”
resurrect as long as someone is healing him/her.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>If the Cleric has to heal him/herself, complete heal will require half
the mana gained (400 of 800).<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Of
course, should the Cleric be casting lower level revive or resuscitate, the Rod will provide a more assistance, although healing the damage the
Rod does to the Cleric will require the same mana to undo.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><b><font face='Arial' size='2' color='#000000'>Conclusion:
</font></b></p>
<p><b><span style='color: red'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Rod will help in mass resurrections, but doesn’t offer significant improvement
in the overall efficiency.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Note
that once this is competed, the rods would likely be replaced.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>That will shift the mana drain from the Cleric to the Magician.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>(Replacing 6 rods will require 1200 mana.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The rods provided the Cleric with 800 mana.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Further, mana was spent healing the Cleric).</font></span></b></p>
<p><b><span style='color: red'><font face='Arial' size='2'><o:p>&nbsp; </o:p>
</font>
</span></b></p>
<p><b><font face='Arial' size='2'><u>Scenario 3 – Overwhelming Odds</u><o:p>
</o:p>
</font></b></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>There are many, many scenarios.
<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;</span>Far too many for me to cover all of
them.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>I’ll have to be general in
my analysis of this scenario.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>When
a party is faced with overwhelming odds, those odds come from: a single mob that
is too powerful for the group’s current condition and/or level or too many
mobs for the group’s current condition and/or level.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>In either case, the group can choose to try to fight or to
flee.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Should the group decide to stand and fight, how
much extra damage can the group do by using the rods?<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>“Damage Boost” is the
percent of mana the Rod supplied to the percent of overall damage delivered for
the spell.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>This can be calculated
in one of three ways:<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Average Case</b>:
Go strictly by the numbers.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>The Rod
supplies a percent of the mana for a spell and therefore boosts the damage
potential by that percentage.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Take
the highest DD the caster can toss and multiply its damage by the percent of
mana the Rod can supply.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Typical
Case</b>: Most casters have more than one
offensive spell memorized.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Typically,
these have different mana requirements.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>For
example, a Magician may have both Lava Bolt and Shock of Swords memorized.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>In this case, the last offensive cast of the Magician may be
“boosted” from Shock of Swords to Lava Bolt with the extra 150 mana from the
Rod.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Whatever additional damage
done by the player with the Rod over the player without the Rod is the increase
in damage potential the Rod has given.<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Maximum
Case</b>: The caster did not have enough mana
to even cast their “second” offensive spell until they used the Rod.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>In this case, without the Rod, the player would not have cast anything,
but would have just stood there like a bump on a log.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>The entire damage done by the player’s “second tier spell” is the
damage potential of the Rod.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>This
won’t likely happen often as high-level DD spells require a lot more than 150
mana.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Further, the range of mana
for this case to come into play is small.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Taking
the Magician example, for this case to apply, the Magician must have 100 mana,
which when combined with the Rod’s 150 mana will be enough to cast Shock of
Swords.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>But if the Magician had 250
mana, the Magician could cast Shock of Swords without the Rod.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>The chance that this situation will occur for all party
members simultaneously is rare (speculation). <o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
