<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Notice an interesting
statistic.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>The average damage and
typical damage are generally centered around 333.&nbsp; Given this, we can
summarize the Rod’s effect as doing 225 damage to the user in exchange for an
average of 333 damage to the target.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Total
party damage (using ADB) is 1544 against a living target.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>Not enough to kill many level 44+ mobs..<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font size='2' face='Arial'><b>Caveats:<o:p>
</o:p>
</b></font></p>
<ul style='margin-top:0in' type='disc'>
  <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .5in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>I
    chose spells from each class to illustrate what I felt were fair
    calculations.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>I only play the Magician
    class.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>I may not have
    chosen what someone who plays a specific class above would have chosen. <o:p>
    </o:p>
    </font></li>
  <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .5in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The
    above calculations are to show damage in an emergency situation.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
    </span>Therefore, only direct damage spells were used.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
    </span>DOTs were ignored as being too slow to save the party from being
    overwhelmed.<o:p>
    </o:p>
    </font></li>
  <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .5in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>Maximum
    damage were used.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Lower level
    spells may be less likely to stick, but are also less likely to get
    interrupted. <span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;</span>Higher-level
    spells are also more likely to fizzle.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
    </span>I don’t have the numbers for all of that.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
    </span>Therefore, your mileage may vary.<o:p>
    </o:p>
    </font></li>
  <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list .5in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>There
    are many ways to combine the above and create different scenarios that
    don’t involve straight damage.<o:p>
    </o:p>
    </font></li>
  <ul style='margin-top:0in' type='disc'>
    <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level2 lfo2;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The
      Cleric may use the Rod’s effect to cast a heal.<o:p>
      </o:p>
      </font></li>
    <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level2 lfo2;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The
      Enchanter may use the Rod’s effect to summon an animation, charm or
      stun.<o:p>
      </o:p>
      </font></li>
    <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level2 lfo2;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The
      Magician may use the Rod’s effect to summon a pet.<o:p>
      </o:p>
      </font></li>
    <li class='MsoNormal' style='mso-list:l2 level2 lfo2;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The
      Wizard may use the Rod’s effect to evacuate the party.<o:p>
      </o:p>
      </font></li>
  </ul>
</ul>
<p style='tab-stops:list 2.0in'><b><font color='#000000' face='Arial' size='2'>Conclusion:</font></b></p>
<p style='tab-stops:list 2.0in'><b><span style='color: red'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The
damage potential of a caster is raised approximately 333 points at a sacrifice
of 225 health points on the part of its user.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>To get this benefit, a Magician must invest 200 mana points in the Rod prior to the battle.<span style='mso-spacerun:
yes'>&nbsp; </span>The use of the Rod is therefore limited in that typically, it
will do only 48% more damage to a mob than to the player that uses it.</font></span></b></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Should the group decide to
flee, how much use is a Rod?</b>&nbsp;<o:p>
</o:p>
</font></p>
<p><font face='Arial' size='2'>This one is easy.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>All evacuate spells are 300 mana.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>The
Rod might be able to cover a fizzle, but the Wizard or druid will need at least
150 mana before the Rod is of any use.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>Note
that using multiple rods in this scenario is possible, it isn’t real viable as
players would need to pass them to the caster while taking hits.</font></p>
<p><b><font face='Arial' size='2'>Caveats:<o:p>
</o:p>
</font>
</b></p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <font face='Arial' size='2'>Typically in the planes and on
    raids, very large groups go into the zone.&nbsp; You simply don’t evacuate when things get bad on a raid.&nbsp;
    If members are dying, they are healed or they die to be resurrected
    when possible.&nbsp; Therefore, the Rod will not be of use for evacuate unless the entire raiding party (all
    groups) calls for an evacuate and the casters have at least 150 mana, but
    less than 300.

    </font></li>
  <li>
<font face='Arial' size='2'>In my own experience, evacuate
    was called early against mobs we could not hope to beat.  There’s little point in standing and fighting when things go so
    horribly wrong, death is certain (not talking about planes or dragon raids).&nbsp;
    Generally this means the Wizard or druid is protected as much as
    possible while they try to evacuate.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span>In
    this case the Rod will be of little use since the caster will still have
    plenty of mana.</font></li>
</ul>
<p><b><font color='#000000' face='Arial' size='2'>Conclusion:</font></b></p>
<p><b><span style='color: red'><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Rod has a very small chance of being needed to evacuate the party.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp;
</span>If that chance comes up and the spell is successfully cast, the benefits
are huge.<span style='mso-spacerun: yes'>&nbsp; </span></font></span></b></p>
<p><b><span style='color: red'><font face='Arial' size='2'>&nbsp;
